Merge pull request #403 from mannodermaus/remove-support-jars Add AAR-to-JAR plugin to decouple processor's test scope from Android
Merge branch 'master' of https://github.com/permissions-dispatcher/PermissionsDispatcher into remove-support-jars

Add AAR-to-JAR plugin to decouple processor's test scope from Android The annotation processor required knowledge of Android classes
in order to perform its unit tests for code generation. Therefore,
we used to have two JAR versions of support-v4 & support-v13 in its
src/test/libs folder, which haven't been updated in quite some time.
Additionally, we had to mock out android.provider.Settings manually,
just to make the test scope compile, since we depended on the library
project directly through declaration in the processor's build script
(sourceSets.test.java.srcDir).

With this commit, these archaic discrepancies are laid to rest, and
replaced with a cleaner separation between Java and Android for our
processor. No dependencies are leaking into our compilation classpath
anymore, so the processor doesn't have to depend on the library's Android
stuff explicitly anymore. Instead, we utilize a new Gradle plugin which
generates "JAR stubs" from AAR libraries to provide a mere facade for
code generation tests.

There's two parts to this: First, a new plugin inside our "buildSrc"
project takes care of converting AAR dependencies of the processor project
to JAR, using a custom configuration called "testCompileAar". It also
records the location of the converted JAR stubs into a resource file
accessible by the processor's test scope. Secondly, this resource file
is used to construct an enhanced classpath which is "Android-aware", then
provided to our code generation tests in TestSuite.java.

This will also pave the way to finally rid ourselves of the two source
directories inside the library projects. There's nothing really stopping
us from putting all the annotations inside their own module now, leaving
only PermissionUtils.java in the library project, and removing the
additional srcDir declaration from the processor project. This would be
replacible by a dependency on the annotation project!

Replace deprecated "com.google.android" dependency with android.jar A small custom Gradle plugin is used to look up the user's android.jar
and provide its path as a file dependency to Gradle scripts. With this,
we can finally get rid of the ancient dependency on the Android SDK
present in the processor's test scope, which prevented us from specifying
the Marshmallow Build Constant inside the library. Instead, the plugin
obtains configuration parameters to search & find the user's SDK installation
and grab a reference to the android.jar, which contains the more up-to-date
classes for the processor.

Merge pull request #342 from aurae/318_deterministic_reproducible_builds Allow for Deterministic, Reproducible Builds with sorted inputs

Allow for Deterministic, Reproducible Builds with sorted inputs The annotation processor uses a RequestCodeProvider to assign unique
request codes to each annotated @NeedsPermission method. This shared
state collides with the non-deterministic nature of the processor's
RoundEnvironment, since we can't guarantee the processing order by default.

Here, we sort the affected sets of data before starting the iterations.
First, the annotated @RuntimePermissions classes need to be in the same
order every time we build. Second, inside each annotated class, the
annotated @NeedsPermission methods also need to be in the same order.
Using simple "sortedBy" predicates, this is achieved.
